<div id="other-internet-resources">

<h2 id="Oth">Other Internet Resources</h2>

<ul>
 <li><a href="https://asm.org/" target="other">American Society for Microbiology</a>.
 Lots of links to news, ASM publications, and various microbiological
topics, including historical material.</li>
 <li><a href="https://asm.org/Podcasts/TWiM" target="other">This Week in Microbiology</a>:
 podcasts on microbial matters, run by the American Society for
Microbiology.</li>
 <li><a href="https://microbiologysociety.org/" target="other">The Microbiology Society</a>,
 the main microbiology organization in the UK. Lots of outreach and
resources.</li>
 <li><a href="https://fems-microbiology.org/" target="other">Federation of European Microbiological Societies</a>:
 represents 50 societies, and has numerous links, including some
historical background.</li>
 <li><a href="https://www.nzms.org.nz/" target="other">Te Manat&#333;p&#363; M&#257;tai Koiora Moroiti o Aotearoa / NZ Microbiological Society</a>.</li>
 <li><a href="https://www.theasm.org.au/" target="other">Australian Society for Microbiology</a>.</li>
 <li><a href="https://www.isme-microbes.org/" target="other">International Society for Microbial Ecology</a>
 &ndash; just one example of a subdisciplinary focus. Lots of links to
its own journal and other material.</li>
 <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microbiology" target="other">Wikipedia page on microbiology</a>
 &ndash; many useful links.</li>
 <li><a href="https://microbewiki.kenyon.edu/index.php/MicrobeWiki" target="other">Microbe Wiki</a>
 with lots of curated resources, including educational material.
Edited and informative.</li>
 <li><a href="https://microbiomedigest.com/" target="other">Microbiome Digest</a>.
 A regularly updated report of new microbiome papers. Initiated by
Elisabeth Bik, now maintained by volunteers.</li>
 <li><a href="https://schaechter.asmblog.org/" target="other">Small Things Considered</a>.
 A regularly updated blog about all things unicellular, started by
Elio Schaechter and continued by Roberto Kolter and an enthusiastic
team of microbiophiles.</li>
 <li><a href="https://telliamedrevisited.wordpress.com/" target="other">Telliamed Revisited</a>.
 Richard Lenski&rsquo;s intermittent blog about microbial goings on
(including viruses).</li>
 <li><a href="https://phylogenomics.blogspot.com/p/blog-page.html" target="other">The Tree of Life</a>.
 Jonathan Eisen&rsquo;s list of material &lsquo;overselling the
microbiome&rsquo;. Links to analyses plus original material 2018 and
earlier.</li>
 <li><a href="https://microbialmenagerie.com/" target="other">Microbial Menagerie</a>.
 A regularly updated site on microbial and microbiological news by
Jennifer Tsang.</li>
 <li><a href="http://www.microbialart.com/" target="other">Microbial Art</a>:
 a curated gallery of artwork created with and about
microorganisms.</li>
</ul>
</div>

